This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new framework for training Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) that improves their convergence and mode coverage. The paper also discusses the difficulty of training GANs in practice, which is a common problem in the field of machine learning. 

The paper also mentions the use of GANs for generating low-resolution images, which suggests that it could also belong to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision). 

Additionally, the paper proposes an improved variant of the Generative Adversarial Metric, which is a tool for evaluating the quality of GANs. This suggests that the paper could also belong to the sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) or cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), which are both concerned with developing and evaluating machine learning algorithms. 

Finally, the paper discusses the use of multiple GANs trained simultaneously, which could be seen as a game-theoretic problem. This suggests that the paper could also belong to the sub-category of cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
